<TEXT>
a century after the vatican lost control of rome 
politicians are accusing it of still trying to control the citys 
politics 
the charge stems from a speech by a top church administrator 
the papal vicar for rome suggesting that the citys voters choose 
the christian democrats italys only churchlinked party in 
mayoral elections this weekend 
the appeal by cardinal ugo poletti has sparked a national outcry 
about roman catholic church involvement in italian politics 
we seem to have returned to the rome of the popes commented 
bettino craxi leader of the socialist party 
the debate underlines how powerful religion is considered even 
in a city that appears overwhelmingly secular with low mass 
attendance porno movie houses and condom ads on buses it has 
overshadowed such pressing concerns as traffic pollution social 
services and housing 
poletti came under attack particularly for saying voters should 
make courageous choices even at the expense of personal 
sacrifice or repugnance 
his statement was interpreted as calling for support for the 
christian democrats despite the fact that successive city 
governments led by the party have been embroiled in scandal 
it is worrying that cardinal poletti invites people to 
vote for the christian democrats even when they feel 
repugnance said giorgio la malfa leader of the small republican 
party 
since july rome has been run by a special commissioner named by 
the national government after christian democrat mayor pietro 
giubilo resigned giubilo had been accused of steering contracts 
for school lunches to friends he denied he did anything wrong 
while the elections are simply to choose a city council which 
in turn elects the mayor they have major symbolic significance 
both for the church and the italian political parties 
the oct 2930 ballot is the first since the christian democrats 
won back control of city hall in 1985 after nine years of rule by 
the communists italys secondbiggest party 
the vatican was embarrassed by communist rule in the city of 
popes and unhappy about several communist policies such as 
extension of abortion services consequently it is anxious to see a 
party espousing catholic values returned to city hall 
political parties meanwhile see the rome elections as a 
barometer of their popularity nationwide and a chance to land a 
highprofile post 
the importance of the vote has prompted several parties to send 
top politicians including premier giulio andreotti a christian 
democrat to stump for mayoral candidates craxi sailed down the 
tiber river to promote his man tourism minister franco carraro 
the vatican controlled the city of rome for 400 years until 
italian unification hero giuseppe garibaldis troops entered the 
city in 1870 
but the church has long kept a hand in italian politics and its 
support of the christian democrats has been credited with helping 
keep the communists out of national government for more than four 
decades 
much of the churchs traditional influence however has waned 
in italy as western european society has become more secular 
less than 25 percent of the population attends mass regularly in 
the city that is the world center of catholicism 
only about 72 percent of marriages in the italian capital this 
year were in church even though around 90 percent of the 
population calls itself catholic according to figures from city 
hall and the catholic organization caritas 
still the catholic church is considered a powerful political 
force in the eternal city 
the turinbased newspaper la stampa recently surveyed the 
strength of romes religious orders and lay catholic organizations 
and concluded they comprised around 60000 people rome has 23 
million eligible voters 
more than 39 percent of romans questioned in a survey in the 
italian newsmagazine panorama felt cardinal polettis appeal would 
have a lot or some influence on the votes of catholics 
the latest controversy came as the vatican has been sparring 
with christian democrat politicians over conditions in the capital 
in february pope john paul ii urged city officials to stop 
squabbling among themselves he described rome as a city of two 
faces where wealth and poverty exist side by side 
both poletti and the vatican newspaper osservatore romano were 
critical of giubilo the mayor who resigned 
the fact that poletti urged support for the party he had been 
criticizing was not lost on politicians 
</TEXT>
