<TEXT>
a study suggests the nutritional needs of 
women with eating disorders differ from those of normal women 
a study by western psychiatric institute and clinic found that 
women recovering from bulimia needed only 73 percent of the normal 
intake of calories conversely women recovering from anorexia 
needed twothirds more calories than normal 
bulimia is the disorder of gorging and purging anorexia is an 
avoidance of food 
the study of 23 recovering bulimic women who were trying to 
maintain normal weight found that the women required only 10 
calories per pound of body weight or 73 percent of the 138 daily 
calories per pound that healthy women need 
separate studies involving 31 recovering anorexic women found 
they needed 223 calories per pound of body weight to maintain 
their normal weight 
these findings have led to new treatment methods in our 
program and they help us to understand the physiological 
factors that complicate the psychological issues of eating 
disorders said dr walter kaye director of the institutes 
center for overcoming problem eating 
the findings were published in a recent issue of the american 
journal of nutrition and released to the public tuesday in 
conjunction with easting disorders awareness week 
the studies were conducted during the last three years kaye 
said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

