<TEXT>
any effort by president bush to exercise a 
lineitem veto will prompt a lawsuit by members of congress the 
chairman of a house judiciary subcommittee says 
the lineitem veto is an idea that many of us would resist 
very diligently rep don edwards dcalif chairman of the 
civil and constitutional rights subcommittee of the house judiciary 
committee said tuesday after white house spokesman marlin 
fitzwater said bush was considering such a move 
bush fitzwater said is prepared to take such a step despite 
lack of specific constitutional authority to see if it works 
although bush has called for a constitutional amendment to give 
him the ability to veto just one item in a bill while leaving the 
rest intact such a proposal has never made much headway in 
congress 
former president reagan tried unsuccessfully for eight years to 
persuade congress to propose such a constitutional change to the 
states for ratification 
some legal scholars contend that lineitem veto powers are 
implied in a presidents overall veto power however the concept 
has never been tested 
such a notion edwards said in an interview comes from chit 
chat in conservative circles and has little constitutional 
legitimacy 
we are looking for a vehicle that might be a suitable test 
case but at this point we dont have one fitzwater said adding 
that it was anticipated such a move would provoke a court challenge 
were bush to cast such a veto edwards said a majority of the 
members of the judiciary committee would promptly take him to 
court 
