<TEXT>
edward ware barrett a leading figure in 
american journalism who founded the columbia journalism review has 
died after a long illness he was 79 
barrett died monday at greenwich hospital in connecticut he had 
been inactive since suffering a stroke five years ago 
in addition to establishing the review in 1962 barrett served 
as dean of columbia universitys graduate school of journalism from 
1956 to 1968 
barrett was the quintessential dean who set the standards for 
the school and brought it to great heights said fred w 
friendly director of the columbia seminars on media and society 
no one in my lifetime has contributed more to journalists 
understanding of journalism 
norman isaacs onetime chairman of the nowdefunct national 
news council said ed barrett was one of the great pioneers in 
trying to lead american journalism into public accountability 
barrett was born july 3 1910 in birmingham ala the son of 
the editorpublisher of the birmingham ageherald a 1932 princeton 
graduate he worked briefly for cbs before joining newsweek as a 
researcherwriter in 1933 
he became washington correspondent national editor and 
associate editor for newsweek staying there until joining the war 
effort in 1942 as chief of what became the office of strategic 
services 
he went back to newsweek from 1946 to 1950 before returning to 
government service as assistant secretary of state 
columbia journalism review was the first national magazine 
devoted to journalistic criticism he was publisher and editorial 
chairman from 1975 through 1982 when he became publisher emeritus 
he is survived by his wife of 50 years mason and two 
daughters margo of new york city and lisa of burlington vt 
the funeral service will be friday at 4 pm in greenwich conn 
with friendly delivering the eulogy 
the family has asked for contributions to the edward w barrett 
fund at the columbia journalism review in lieu of flowers 
</TEXT>
