the constitutional change throwing all seats in parliament up 
for popular election was approved by the supreme soviet tuesday in 
a 254to85 vote however it must be confirmed by the 
legislatures parent body the congress of peoples deputies which 
meets at the end of the year 
the change part of a package of constitutional amendments 
approved tuesday denies the communist party and other special 
interests their guaranteed seats 
last years political reform allocated 100 seats to the 
communist party which filled them by allowing the leadership to 
select just 100 candidates 
that allowed gorbachev and most of the ruling politburo to be 
seated in congress without facing a public vote of confidence 
the supreme soviet the 542member fulltime legislature did 
not require gorbachev to mount a national campaign to win 
reelection to the presidency although some deputies had suggested 
a direct election that post will continue to be filled by the 
congress from among its members 
the decision by no means restricts the communist party from 
running candidates for geographical seats currently 80 percent of 
the 2250 deputies are communist party members 
last years political reform gave soviet voters their first real 
selection of candidates but the election system was complex and 
many people complained that the process was undemocratic and 
favored the status quo 
twothirds of the 2250 deputies in the congress were elected 
from geographical districts the other onethird were elected by 
social organizations and the reform package promised 100 seats 
each to the communist party the official trade unions and 
cooperative organizations 
the package allocated 75 seats each to the komsomol communist 
youth league to creative unions and to groups of women academics 
and veterans 
the last 75 were split among smaller groups with one seat even 
going to an association of stamp collectors 
progressives complained that the system violated the principle 
of one person one vote they said members of these organizations 
had the opportunity to vote in each group as well as in their 
geographical district 
in practice key reform groups such as the baltic peoples 
fronts and groups of new private business cooperatives were shut 
