with the nato pact and they are still members of the mutual 
council on economic assistance he said 
despite a bloody history the soviets and finns have close 
business ties based for many years on the barter of soviet oil for 
finnish goods 
finland still is the soviets secondlargest trading partner in 
the capitalist world after west germany but its own trade 
dependency on the soviet union declined as oil prices plunged 
the finns increasingly have turned toward western europe and 
shifted their economy from basic industries and shipbuilding to 
electronics and high technology 
finlands trade with the soviets fell from 25 percent of its 
total exports in 1983 to just 13 percent this year at the same 
time its own economy became one of the fastest growing in the west 
expanding about 5 percent a year 
the two countries share a 793mile border 
in 1948 finland and the soviet union signed a treaty of 
friendship and cooperation which guaranteed the soviets 
northwestern front finland adopted a cautious neutral foreign 
policy which now is being held up as a model by reformers in the 
baltic states and others in the soviet sphere 
as of next year residents of estonia and the other baltic 
republics will take over management of their local economies from 
moscow opening the way for further finnish and western involvement 
finland already has daily ferry service to tallinn the estonian 
capital and residents of the two regions which are linguistic and 
cultural cousins can watch each others television 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

