an earthquake that hit oaklands side of the bay in 1836 was 
followed by a quake on the san francisco side in 1838 and an 
earthquake that hit the san francisco peninsula in 1865 was 
followed by an oakland quake three years later all the earthquakes 
had magnitudes of 63 to 70 
the 1865 earthquake occurred near the loma prieta area of the 
san francisco peninsula where the oct 17 earthquake occurred 
according to a report to appear friday in science magazine 
an oakland quake similar in size on the richter scale to the 
oct 17 earthquake would cause far more damage said allan lindh of 
the us geological survey in menlo park calif as horrible as 
this one is its just nothing compared to when we get an 
earthquake this size in the urban areas in and near oakland he 
told science 
lindh could not be reached wednesday 
lindh william ellsworth and their colleagues in menlo park 
report that the 70 years leading up to the big san francisco 
earthquake of 1906 were marked by numerous earthquakes and that 
activity was sharply reduced after the big quake 
in a telephone interview lynn sykes a seismologist at the 
lamontdoherty geological observatory of columbia university in 
palisades ny said there are reasons to believe the two sides of 
the bay are seismologically linked 
just as there was activity in the oakland area before the 1906 
earthquake there was activity there before the oct 17 quake 
sykes said 
there were a number of magnitude 5 to magnitude 6 earthquakes 
in the east bay starting around 1973 he said i would say in 
both instances the stress or pressures in the earth were building 
up he said 
the question now is did the oct 17 quake relieve pressures 
that had been building in the east bay or did it increase 
pressures there making a matching quake likely 
its too soon toth graf the deaths adds 3 
grafs with baker reaction 
</TEXT>
