<TEXT>
a panel of rural appraisers says farmland 
values are expected to continue rising in 1990 but at a much 
slower rate than this year the agriculture department reported 
wednesday 
based on a survey made in early august farmland prices are 
likely to rise an average 35 percent by august 1990 that would 
be about half the 65 percent increase reported for 198889 
one reason suggested by appraisers for the slowdown is a drop 
in corn and soybean prices from the droughtlevels of last year 
but higher wheat prices probably are helping support some values 
particularly in the great plains 
a group of about 500 appraisers is checked quarterly by a 
university of wisconsin survey laboratory for the departments 
economic research service said analyst roger hexem author of the 
report 
hexem said in a telephone interview that the yearahead estimate 
by appraisers was somewhat lower than we have been forecasting 
within the agency the information is being reviewed and will be 
considered when usda issues its next farmland forecast late in 
november 
the report said appraisers expect land values to rise the 
fastest in the north central region up 48 percent during the 
198990 compared with a 95 percent increase reported in 198889 
no state estimates were included in the report 
while corn and soybean prices remain relatively high compared 
with recent years current prices are lower than last year and may 
have contributed to the lessoptimistic outlook the report said 
in contrast high and rising wheat prices are llikely providing 
strength to the regions land values 
in the south appraisers expect land values to increase an 
average of 27 percent in 198990 compared with 55 percent the 
previous 12 months 
principal factors behind the 27 percent increase expected in 
the south are commodity price movements lower interest rates and 
improving farm incomes the report said during the past year 
the appraisers said high commodity prices government programs and 
favorable weather contributed to higher farmland values in the 
south 
farmland in the west was forecast by appraisers to appreciate 
about 3 percvent compared with 41 percent in 198889 
high commodity prices including cattle and stronger demand 
by nonagricultural investors are the most frequently cited factors 
behind the increases the report said 
values in the northeast are expected to rise an average of 14 
percent in 198990 compared with 28 percent the previous year 
