<TEXT>
for the second time in five weeks a sailor 
stationed aboard the aircraft carrier uss midway has been convicted 
of espionage the navy said on wednesday 
navy spokesman lt james wood identified the second sailor who 
was sentenced to 10 years confinement at hard labor as electonics 
warfare technician petty officer third class russell p brown of 
norfolk neb 
brown 21 was convicted for conspiring with airman recruit 
james r wilmoth to commit espionage and for making false 
statements to the naval investigative service wood said 
wilmoth 21 of omaha neb was sentenced last month to 35 
years for trying to pass classified material to a soviet agent 
the sailors were arrested by nis on july 25 in yokosuka japan 
where the midway is based 
they were apprehended after an eightmonth investigation wood 
said 
no other sailors have been implicated in the case the 
spokesman said 
besides his 10year sentence brown received a dishonorable 
discharge reduction in rank from paygrade e3 to e1 and 
forfeiture of all pay and allowances wood said 
the navy spokesman said a general court martial was convened and 
charges against brown referred to a trial by a military judge at 
the order of the commander of the us seventh fleet vice adm 
henry h mauz jr 
the sailors twoday trial began oct 18 in yokosuka wood said 
the spokesman said brown pleaded not guilty and his case will be 
reviewed by the fleet commander before he begins serving his 
sentence 
wilmoth who worked in food service aboard the aircraft carrier 
also was convicted of possession and distribution of hashish navy 
spokesman lt greg smith said last month 
wood said wilmoth did not have a security clearance but that 
brown had one 
the spokesman said he could not provide any details of the 
classified information involved in the case 
asked about a report that brown took classified documents from a 
receptacle used to hold such documents slated for burning in the 
electronics warfare center of the carrier wood said he could not 
comment 
that is part of the investigation that is still going on 
wood said 
wilmoths court martial was in yokosuka as well and he was 
convicted on sept 24 on charges of attempted espionage failure to 
report a contact with a soviet citizen conspiracy to unlawfully 
transfer classified material and possession use and distribution 
of hashish 
wilmoth who also received a dishonorable discharge had been in 
the navy for 2 12 years and had served aboard the midway since may 
1988 smith said 
brown had been in the navy the same period of time as wilmoth 
and had been stationed aboard the aircraft carrier since may 1987 
wood said 
