<TEXT>
a house committee has approved legislation 
requiring the federal trade commission to adopt new rules designed 
to stem multibilliondollar telephone sales fraud 
the house energy and commerce committee on a voice vote 
tuesday approved a bill by rep thomas a luken dohio that 
would order the ftc to establish a minimum set of standards on 
socalled telemarketing within 180 days 
the rules must give buyers the right to change their minds 
within a certain time after placing a phone order and require 
refunds if the goods arent delivered by a specified date 
the ftc also must establish restrictions on the time of day when 
phone solicitations may be made 
in addition the bill allows private citizens and state 
officials to sue in federal court anyone who violates the new ftc 
rules or commits telemarketing fraud prohibits harassment of 
customers by telemarketing firms and directs the commission to set 
up an office to answer consumer questions 
a nearly identical measure passed the house last year on a voice 
vote but died in the senate 
telephone fraud has grown widely in recent years as hustlers 
offer phony prizes or try to sell goods such as gemstones and rare 
coins or shoddy merchandise 
luken said the ftc had estimated there is 1 billion a year in 
telemarketing fraud private estimates have put the figure much 
higher luken added 
the telephone is becoming an instrument to reach out and rob 
someone luken said 
the bill was designed to make telemarketing rules conform with 
15yearold ftc restrictions on doortodoor and mailorder sales 
said benjamin cohen an aide to luken 
the commission earlier this month began formal proceedings to 
extend the mailorder regulations to telephone sales 
the bill had the support of the banking industry this year 
which has asserted it is losing several hundred million dollars a 
year when dissatisfied customers stop payment on visa or mastercard 
purchases made by phone cohen added 
before it approved the bill the committee gave voicevote 
approval to an amendment offered by rep thomas j manton dny 
that specifies that the new ftc rules will not apply to securities 
which are covered by the securities and exchange commission 
the sec two months ago adopted a penny stock rule requiring 
that the buyer must give the seller written confirmation before the 
sale is consummated 
thats tougher than anything in our bill cohen said 
in other action tuesday the committee on a voice vote 
authorized 1098 million for the federal communications commission 
in the 1990 fiscal year the year that began oct 1 and 1215 
million next year up from 996 million in the 1989 fiscal year 
the fcc authorization was amended by rep bill richardson 
dnm to allow the fcc to consider what impact its rulings may 
have on us trade 
richardson said the provision was a response to the decision 
last month of the european common market to urge its 12 member 
nations to broadcast television programs made in the market at 
least 51 percent of the time where practicable 
he said amendment was a strong signal that until foreign 
telecommunications markets are completely open to us companies 
the united states will be watching its own interests carefully 
the senate commerce science and transportation committee 
earlier this month authorized 1098 million for the fcc in 1990 
but only 1198 million for 1991 
the house committee also authorized 293 million for the 
commerce departments national telecommunications and information 
administration for 1990 and 1991 
