<TEXT>
statistics showing that black mortgage 
applicants are rejected twice as often as whites indicate federal 
regulators arent trying hard enough to enforce discrimination 
laws a senate banking subcommittee chairman says 
the problem today is not lack of laws it is lackluster 
enforcement said sen alan j dixon dill chairman of the 
consumer and regulatory affairs panel 
blacks applying for mortgages at savings institutions are 
rejected approximately twice as often as whites according to data 
collected since 1978 by the office of thrift supervision 
however robert j herrmann senior deputy at the office of the 
comptroller of the currency said only 16 of the 37000 written 
complaints received by his agency between january 1987 and august 
1989 alleged racial discrimination in mortgage lending 
all 16 were investigated and no violations were found he said 
studies by the federal reserve board show that predominantly 
black neighborhoods in atlanta boston cleveland and detroit 
received fewer home purchase loans than white neighborhoods with 
similar income levels 
im not a statistician but when blacks are getting their loan 
applications rejected twice as often as whites i conclude that 
discrimination is part of the problem dixon said tuesday 
regulators told his panel the data doesnt prove violations by 
financial institutions which are prohibited from discriminating 
against potential borrowers on the basis of race sex religion 
national origin or family status 
jonathan l fiechter senior deputy director of the thrift 
office said the statistics only suggest the possibility of 
unequal treatment because they dont include information on the 
income or credit worthiness of mortgage applicants 
john p laware a member of the federal reserve board said 
differences in lending to black and white neighborhoods could be 
explained in part by differences in demand for mortgages 
moreover regulators said their examinations find few banks not 
living up to their obligations 
john f bovenzi deputy to the chairman of the federal deposit 
insurance corp said only 21 of 6515 banks examined for redlining 
violations in 1986 1987 and 1988 received less than satisfactory 
ratings 
herrmann and laware said discrimination is often difficult to 
detect because it can occur when institutions subtly discourage 
loan applications from minorities when there are no applications 
there are no audit trails for examiners to follow they said 
allen j fishbein general counsel for the center for community 
change an activist group in washington said the department of 
housing and urban development could remedy that by expanding its 
use of testers 
testing is an investigative technique using matched pairs of 
homeseekers minority and nonminority who are otherwise 
similarly qualified financial institutions have resisted the use 
of that tactic even though it is already used to detect 
discrimination by real estate and rental agents 
