<TEXT>
the new head of the securities and exchange 
commission told a congressional panel today the handling of wall 
streets 190 point plunge on oct 13 shows the value of the 
market improvements adopted during the past two years 
sec chairman richard c breeden who noted i was sworn into 
office just two weeks ago today was the star witness before a 
house panel on market reform his first public appearance since 
taking office 
it also was breedens first public questioning since the dow 
jones industrial average plunged 19058 points on oct 13 
the dow jones average a key market indicator rebounded to 
close up 8812 points the following monday after a week of gentler 
fluctuations it seesawed again tuesday finishing the day with a 
slight decline of 369 points at 265922 
we learned important lessons from the market turbulence of 
oct 13 and oct 16 and the markets responses to it breeden 
said in testimony prepared for the house energy and commerce 
committees telecommunications and finance subcommittee 
the volume surges and volatility experienced on those two days 
exemplify fundamental changes in our markets they were not 
isolated instances we should not panic in the face of these 
events however for what was demonstrated on oct 13 and 16 was 
the strength and resiliency of the nations markets 
he noted that more shares were traded in one hour during the 
oct 13 slide than were traded on the average full day in 1985 
and three times the markets average daily volume 10 years ago 
breeden also said communication among the financial markets was 
excellent and circuitbreakers temporary trading halts in options 
to slow market volatility also worked well 
legislation is pending in both the senate and the house that 
would expand the secs powers to monitor the markets in several 
ways some of them opposed by various segments of the industry and 
one giving the sec the power to halt trading in emergencies 
opposed by breeden himself 
the other proposed changes include giving the sec authority to 
request reports on large securities and options trades this power 
would enhance the secs surveillence abilities to track whos 
trading what to whom another would require rules for assessing the 
financial soundness of holding companies that are the parent 
companies of brokerdealers 
the other witnesses slated to testify are edward i obrien 
president of the securities industry association a trade 
association representing 600 securities firms and george s 
bissell chairman of the bostonbased keystone group of mutual 
funds 
the market reforms proposed by congress include giving the sec 
chairman the authority to halt trading for up to 24 hours in 
emergenies currently only the president can order such a shutdown 
but breeden has said he does not want that power and does not 
think it should be exercised 
in written answers to senate staffers questions during 
confirmation hearings for the sec post breeden said such authority 
would create too much uncertainty about when the markets would 
close and for how long 
in a crisis this uncertainty and the related rumors 
concerning its likelihood could have seriously adverse 
consequences he wrote last month 
</TEXT>
