<TEXT>
wall street took on a calmer tone today 
following tuesdays rollercoaster ride in which stock prices swung 
wildly depressing the dollar and boosting demand for us treasury 
bonds 
the dow jones average of 30 industrials was off 635 to 265287 
in the first half hour of trading today but in the broader market 
rising stocks held a small edge over losers 
the dow average plummeted as much as 85 points on tuesday before 
rebounding and closing down 369 points at 265922 
analysts said the tone for tuesdays market gyrations was set by 
two factors speculation that a collapsed deal to buy united 
airlines parent ual corp signaled a continued ebbing of the 
takeover tide and concern that a slowing economy would lead to 
weaker corporate profits 
on wall street program trading strategies involving millions of 
shares of stock helped accentuate wild declines and rebounds in 
stock prices some analysts said 
it was almost all computerized program trading that gave us 
tremendous violent price swings said dennis e jarrett a 
technical analyst for kidder peabody amp co i dont think you 
could put your finger on any underlying economic statistic 
in other financial markets tuesday the dollar ended lower 
against most major currencies moving in tandem with the stock 
market and reflecting concern from foreign investors about the 
shakiness of the us financial markets 
but us treasury bonds posted moderate gains with the 
bellwether 30year bond up point or 5 per 1000 face amount 
treasury bonds which are guaranteed by the government are 
considered a safe haven at times of financial instability 
stock market observers initially attributed the downturn to the 
decision late monday by ual to forego an employeemanagement buyout 
for the time being and a surge tuesday in computerized program 
selling involving stockindex futures 
in such program selling traders using sophisticated computer 
programs take advantage of minute price discrepancies between 
stockindex futures and the actual stocks on which the futures 
contracts are based 
the ual buyout groups oct 13 announcement that it couldnt 
raise financing for its 675 billion bid and program selling that 
followed were considered key factors in the dows 190point plunge 
that day stocks regained much of their losses last week however 
its certainly reminiscent of friday the 13th although 
its not a replay said hugh johnson chief investment officer 
for first albany corp in albany 
analysts said program trades dominated tuesdays buying and 
selling 
i didnt see a lot of individuals or even institutions 
participating said johnson by and large they seemed to be 
fence sitting 
gene jay seagle vice president and director of technical 
research at gruntal financial inc said program trading was 
accelerating the current bearishness apparent in the stock market 
what we have here is an intermediate correction in an 
otherwise bull market he said but weve just seen it happen 
in a matter of days instead of weeks as we normally do 
were getting compressed moves both on the upside and the 
downside due to program trading 
johnson said the fixation on the collapse of the ual buyout 
represented concerns about the future of leveraged buyouts 
its not the final nail in the coffin of leveraged buyouts or 
acquisitions but its pretty darn close to it he said the 
lbo business had been the principal drive of the stock market for 
most of 1988 and 1989 
analysts also pinned the blame on the lower stock prices on 
weakness in the economy and its effects on corporate profits those 
concerns were magnified by a government report tuesday showing that 
orders for big ticket durable goods declined 01 percent during 
september 
the economys heartbeat is not very strong and that isnt good 
news for stocks said ac moore director of research at argus 
research in new york 
