<TEXT>
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan said 
today he opposes a bill that would subject the central bank to more 
supervision from congress and the administration 
however congressional supporters of the measure said it was 
needed to make the secretive central bank more accountable for its 
actions which can have enormous impact on the 5 trillion us 
economy 
the federal reserve must take actions that while sometimes 
unpopular in the short run are in the longrun best interests of 
the country greenspan said adding that the independence of 
the federal reserve has in practice served the country well 
greenspan was the leadoff witness as a house banking 
subcommittee opened hearings to examine how the central bank and 
its chairman often called the second most powerful man in america 
reach decisions on setting interest rates 
greenspan said the fed was opposed to a bill sponsored by reps 
lee hamilton dind and byron dorgan dnd which would require 
fed officials to meet at specified times with the administration 
and release immediately results of its closeddoor deliberations 
while rejecting these proposals greenspan did endorse another 
measure sponsored by rep stephen neal dnc that would write 
into law that the feds chief mission is to eliminate inflation and 
establish a deadline of 1994 for having done so 
greenspan said however that wringing inflation out of the 
economy over the next five years would have shorttem costs in 
terms of slower growth 
the hamiltondorgan proposal also calls for the feds budget 
which currently is not reviewed by either congress or the 
administration to be subject to review and would require that the 
feds books be audited each year by congressional auditors it also 
would make the chairmans term start one year after the start of a 
presidential term 
greenspan said all those changes would compromise the political 
independence of the fed which he said was essential to the central 
banks main role of fighting inflation 
in arguing for his proposal hamilton said the purpose of our 
bill is to increase the accountability of the federal reserve to 
the american people by making the workings of the fed more open and 
by establishing a formal channel of communications between 
policymakers 
the hamiltondorgan measure originally called for the secretary 
of the treasury to be added to the feds key policymaking body 
the federal open market committee 
that panel composed of members of the federal reserve board and 
presidents of the feds regional banks meets secretly eight times 
a year to set interest rate policies decisions arent made public 
for six weeks after a meeting and even then only abbreviated 
minutes of the closeddoor sessions are made available 
the revised hamiltondorgan bill drops the effort to put the 
treasury secretary on the feds policy board and instead calls for 
the fed panel to meet twice each year with the treasury secretary 
and other top administration officials it also calls for the 
immediate release of the minutes of the meeting 
neals measure does not include any penalties if the fed fails 
to meet the fiveyear deadline for eliminating inflation 
consumer prices have been rising at an annual rate of 44 
percent through the first nine months of this year 
current law directs the fed to promote effectively the goals 
of maximum employment stable prices and moderate longterm 
interest rates but says nothing about the tradeoffs between 
these sometimesconflicting goals 
the law as it is presently written is so broad that the fed 
can do anything and say that they are following the law neal 
said in arguing for his proposal 
neals original legislation was much more specific in calling on 
the fed to reduce by 1 percent a year until it had reached zero 
inflation 
his new version revamped to meet greenspans objections simply 
calls for the elimination of inflation in five years and 
paraphrases language greenspan has used to say that inflation 
will be deemed to be eliminated when the expected rate of change of 
the general level of prices ceases to be a factor in individual and 
business decisions making 
even the revised bills are given little chance of passing 
congress especially in light of objections from key members of the 
senate banking committee 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

