a burly bearded man uses sign language to 
communicate with his pal as they belly up to the bar in a beer 
advertisement 
an ad for laundry detergent shows a man in a wheelchair 
skyhooking a soap packet into the washing machine an ad for a 
southern bank shows a mother getting her children off to school and 
settling down to read her bank statement written in braille 
advertisers have been making greater use of people with 
disabilities in mainstream commercials designed to show the wide 
appeal of their products and services 
advocates for the more than 37 million physically challenged 
americans have welcomed this increased visibility but they say the 
disabled still are underrepresented 
advertisers have been a bit timid said arney rosenblat 
spokeswoman for the national multiple sclerosis society and an 
advocate of more disabled people in advertising they always try 
to get sexy girls and project a mainstream idea of what everyone 
wants to look like using their product 
but she said a growing awareness of the economic clout of the 
disabled and pressure on congress to forbid discrimination against 
the disabled are having an impact 
she said the disabled have an estimated 40 billion a year in 
spending power an appealing target for manufacturers who have 
shown keener interest in getting messages to narrowly defined 
audiences 
five years ago you couldnt name one company using disabled 
people in commercials but now there are 10 or more ms 
rosenblat said 
