<DOCNO> AP891025-0304 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
kemper financial services inc said wednesday it 
had stopped doing business with four wall street firms involved in 
computerized program trading saying the strategy had scared away 
investors by increasing stock market volatility 
the chicagobased money manager cited what it called the 
disruptive and destabilizing influence of the trading strategy 
which some blame for worsening the 1987 crash and the recent friday 
the 13th plunge 
kemper which has about 75 billion in its stock portfolio out 
of 57 billion in total assets under management said it had ended 
equity business with four firms that conduct program trading for 
their own accounts it did not identify the firms 
the practice of trading millions of shares of stock in seconds 
via computerized buy and sell programs which are used mainly by 
huge institutional investors has been accused of heightening 
stock market price swings that volatility is seen as frightening 
individual investors out of the market 
after the 1987 crash most major brokerages curtailed program 
trading for their own accounts socalled proprietary trading 
but use of the strategy recently has increased 
the new york stock exchange said program trading accounted for 
138 percent of its average daily volume in september up from 103 
percent in august and the highest percentage since the exchange 
began the calculation in july 1988 
some experts recently cited program trading as a factor when the 
dow jones industrial average plummeted more than 190 points in the 
final hours of trading on oct 13 and 85 points this past monday 
morning 
we believe that in the present environment index arbitrage 
generally increases intraday market price volatility which 
undermines investors confidence in the fair functioning of 
markets said stephen timbers kempers chief investment officer 
we hope that this practice stops and prefer to conduct our 
business with brokerage firms who do not engage in this trading 
strategy he said 
index arbitrage is a form of program trading that employs 
computers to rapidly buy and sell huge blocks of stocks in new york 
and stockindex futures in chicago in an attempt to profit from 
minute differences in prices on the two markets 
in september salomon brothers inc morgan stanley amp co 
kidder peabody amp co and goldman sachs amp co conducted the most 
program trading of wall street firms according to the nyse 
goldman and salomon said they were not among the four cut off by 
kemper kidder peabody and bear stearns amp co another major 
programtrading firm declined to comment 
a spokeswoman for morgan stanley which resumed program trading 
in february said the firm does business with kemper but had not 
yet been informed whether it was one of the four 
we believe that our position is reasonable said the 
spokeswoman who asked not to be named during periods of market 
stress we will suspend proprietary arbitrage trading to avoid 
contributing to intraday volatility 
kempers announcement was praised by several other money 
managers who said they also would consider discontinuing placing 
stock orders with brokerages that engage in program trading for 
their own accounts 
i think those guys are terrific said new york money manager 
james cramer of cramer amp co 
we didnt have this horrible kind of volatility when these 
firms were refraining from it cramer said now that theyre 
back we have the volatility 
nobody needs that kind of volatility when theres nothing 
different in the companies outlook said david dreman a 
managing director of dreman value management which has 4 billion 
in assets about 85 percent in stocks 
these methods work absolutely independent of the fundamentals 
in the economy and the stock market 
dreman said a boycott of firms that conduct index arbitrage 
would be very effective and said his firm would consider one if 
clients agreed to it 
defenders said program trading has been made a scapegoat for 
oftennormal market fluctuations they blame market volatility not 
on progam trading but on an overdependence on intermediate dealers 
whose job is to bring together buyers and sellers 
its a shootthemessenger issue said r steven wunsch 
vice president for financial futures at kidder peabody 
arbitragers do bring selling pressure from one market to another 
market but the selling pressure came first they didnt cause it 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

