<DOCNO> AP891025-0306 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mercedesbenz of north america inc has paid 91 
million in corporate taxes on its massachusetts earnings settling 
a case gov michael s dukakis said will be a landmark for other 
states 
the settlement ended a nearly 5year fight between the state and 
the montvale njbased company that had argued it did not owe the 
state a dime and had failed to contest a lawsuit in massachusetts 
courts seeking the payment 
the state won a default judgment against the company in may in 
suffolk county superior court and seized a companyowned car from a 
mercedes executive this summer the 74000 car was auctioned by 
the state and sold for 50000 dukakis said 
massachusetts attorney general james m shannon said the 
settlement was the single largest tax judgment in state history and 
came about when he took steps to seize new jersey property of 
mercedes 
were going to make sure the big guys pay their fair share of 
taxes not just the working men and women of massachusetts 
shannon said 
i hope it is a clear and concise message to all taxpayers 
especially corporate taxpayers that its not just the little guys 
who pay taxes said dukakis who has made collection of 
delinquent taxes a priority in his administration 
mercedesbenz is pleased that its tax dispute with the 
commonwealth of massachusetts has been resolved in an equitable 
manner through goodfaith negotiations initiated by 
mercedesbenz company spokesman bob neary said in montvale 
revenue commissioner stephen w kidder said the case began in 
1985 when his department investigated six foreign car companies he 
said five were cooperative and paid 10 million in taxes but 
mercedes declined until last month 
since then they have been completely cooperative we are 
delighted they have seen the light kidder said 
mercedesbenz had argued it did not owe massachusetts any taxes 
since it had no property in the state and since the imported german 
cars were sold directly to dealers as they left ships in states 
other than massachusetts 
but kidder and shannon said the company had employees based in 
massachusetts to handle warranty matters state lemon law issues 
and to work with dealers 
in order to have to pay corporate taxes in massachusetts a 
company must have some form of connection to the state what tax 
officials call a nexus 
kidder said in most cases it is clear whether or not a company 
must pay 
a chain of retail stores with headquarters in another state owes 
massachusetts corporate taxes on its income from massachusetts 
kidder said while a company that does strictly mailorder business 
from another state does not 
kidder said wednesdays settlement covers mercedes taxes from 
1966 the year the state adopted a corporate excise tax through 
1985 the period covered by the lawsuit 
mercedes intends to file tax returns for the remaining years he 
said 
it was a total victory kidder said 
</TEXT>
